					<tr>
			<td valign="top" colspan="2">
			<p>The <a href="http://www.southesk.com/index.php?option=com_hymn_search&Itemid=46">1962 Hymn Book Search</a> has been a little flaky for some time, and missing some functionality, so following some constructive complaints (!) I have fixed it.</p>

<p>All very well and good, you cry, but how on earth does it work?  Again, following emails with pleas for help, I include here a brief description of how to use the Hymn Search.</p>

<h3>Searching</h3>
<ul>
<li>If you want to simply view a hymn, and you know its number, type it into the <b>Hymn No.</b> box and press Enter or click Search Hymn (from now I will refer to this as "press Enter").</li>
<li>Need to search the text of the Hymn?
<ul>
<li>Well, type a few words into the <b>Search for</b> box and press Enter</li>
<li>Want to limit the search results to a particular meter?  Selecting a Meter from the drop-down list will do just that!</li>
</ul></li>
<li>Looking for a particular author's hymns?  Enter part of the author's name (e.g. <b>dar</b> for J.N.Darby - initials don't work... yet) in the <b>Author</b> box and press Enter.</li>
<li>If you simply want to see all the Hymns for a particular meter but don't want to search for text, leave the <b>Search for</b> and <b>Author</b> boxes empty, select a meter and press Enter.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Note Bene</h3>
<ul>
<li>Selecting a meter and entering an author will not restrict the author's hymns by meter.</li>
<li>If you enter both <b>Search for</b> and <b>Author</b> the search will only filter for text, not author.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Using the Results</h3>
<ul>
<li>The search results are returned on the right half of the page.  Clicking on a Hymn No. loads that Hymn on the left half, and retains your search.</li>
<li>If you have entered an <b>Author</b> and the search returns some authors, you can view view biographies for certain authors if they have a link under their name.  I would like to add more of these - any sources welcomed.</li>
<li>As a handy shortcut, the author's name at the bottom of each Hymn is link - clicking this clears the <b>Search for</b> box, enters the name into the <b>Author</b> box and refreshes.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Multi-Language</h3>
<ul>
<li>The search is currently available for English and German translations.  The Van Den Bergs kindly gave me the Dutch translation an embarrassing length of time ago and I still haven't added it...  I will get round to this too.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Other Search "Dimensions"</h3>
<ul>
<li>There are two classifications of the 1962 Hymn book, useful for study purposes.
<ul>
<li>Alan Davies' version, sent to me recently hard copy in the post (very kindly) by person or persons unknown!</li>
<li>George Murray's version - hoping to find out more about this one soon...</li></ul>
</li>
<li>I have not added these attributes to the Hymns yet (the perennial <b>yet</b>) but plan to do so...</li>
</ul>

<p>I hope this helps!  Feedback welcomed.</p>			</td>
		</tr>
